# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Misconceptions
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------

oakcurric:misconception-everyone-nigeria-similar-viewpoints-future
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Everyone in Nigeria has similar viewpoints about the future of the country’s oil industry."""@en ;
  curric:correction """People are connected to the oil industry in Nigeria in different ways. Different stakeholders often have different ideas and opinions about what the future of Nigeria’s oil industry should look like."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.675897Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-flooding-negative-effects
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Flooding only has negative effects."@en ;
  curric:correction """Flooding is a natural process; it can have positive environmental effects, such as soil replenishment."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.675917Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-plenty-fish-sea
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "There are plenty more fish in the sea."@en ;
  curric:correction """In 2018, nearly 90% of the world’s marine (sea) fish stocks were fully exploited, overexploited or depleted."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.675936Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-russia-entirely-harsh-cold-mountainous
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That Russia is entirely a harsh, cold, mountainous, barren landscape."@en ;
  curric:correction """Some parts of Russia do experience a harsh environment, but Russia is the largest country in the world by area, and so it has a diverse range of environments within it from mountains and volcanoes to vast plains and mighty rivers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.676268Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-confusion-difference-weather-climate
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Confusion about the difference between weather and climate."@en ;
  curric:correction """The weather of a place describes the day to day conditions of the atmosphere. Climate is an average of weather conditions in a place over a long period of time (usually 30 years or more)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.676509Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-plate-boundaries-africa
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "There are no plate boundaries in Africa."@en ;
  curric:correction """Mount Nyiragongo is on a constructive plate boundary known as the East African Rift System, where the African plate is splitting into the Nubian and Somali plates."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.676603Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-world-population-increses-equally-across
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "World population increses equally across the globe."@en ;
  curric:correction """Population is expected to increase in some parts of the world but in other areas the population is expected to decrease."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.678223Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-indigenous-people-traditional-lifestyle
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All Indigenous people have a traditional lifestyle."@en ;
  curric:correction """Indigenous people may have a traditional lifestyle, e.g. reindeer herders, or may have taken on less traditional lifestyles and/or migrated."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.678610Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-soft-rock-physically
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may think that soft rock is physically soft to the touch, like a pillow."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Geologically soft is not the same as being soft like a pillow. All rock feels solid when touched, even soft rocks. Rock that is classified as soft, like clay, can crumble and break more easily than rock which is classified as hard, like granite."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.678689Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-people-live-near-rainforest-use
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Only people that live in/near the rainforest use it."@en ;
  curric:correction """Many products grown/extracted from the rainforest are exported and used by people all over the world."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.678848Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-flooding-caused-physical-factors-such
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Flooding is only caused by physical factors such as heavy rainfall."@en ;
  curric:correction "Human factors can lead to flooding too, such as deforestation."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.679488Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-invasive-species-introduced-humans-intentionally
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Invasive species are always introduced by humans intentionally."@en ;
  curric:correction """While some introductions are intentional (e.g. for pest control or landscaping), many invasive species are introduced accidentally, such as via ballast water in ships or hitchhiking on imported goods."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.679574Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-rainforests-nutritious-soil-such-lot
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Rainforests must have the most nutritious soil as they have such a lot of plants and such tall trees."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Temperate deciduous forests have more nutrient rich soil than other forests as trees lose their leaves, meaning there is a lot of leaf litter and the climate is not too cold for decomposers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.679857Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-anthropocene-period-earths-history-homosapiens
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The Anthropocene is the period of Earth’s history from when homosapiens first evolved."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The Anthropocene is a proposed geological epoch that marks the period in Earth’s history during which human activity has had a significant impact on Earth."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.679864Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-climate-change-global-warming-same
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Climate change and global warming are the same thing."@en ;
  curric:correction """Global warming is the increase in Earth's average temperature over a long period of time, whereas  climate change is a large-scale and long-term change in the planet’s climate, including weather patterns and average temperatures."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.679869Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-everyone-same-views-opinions-importance
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Everyone will have the same views and opinions about the importance of protecting the Sundarbans."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Role play could be used to investgate the perspectives of different stakeholders in the Sundarbans such as fishing communities, farmers, government officials, tourism operators and conservationists."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.679885Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-everything-made-china-exported-other
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Everything made in China is exported to other countries."@en ;
  curric:correction """China manufactures products for people to buy and use in China and countries around the world."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.679896Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-arctic-region-uninhabited
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The Arctic region is uninhabited."@en ;
  curric:correction "Approximately 4 million people live in the Arctic region."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.679960Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-evergreen-coniferous-trees-same
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Evergreen and coniferous trees are the same."@en ;
  curric:correction """Coniferous trees produce cones and are normally evergreen (don't lose their leaves in autumn). Some evergreen trees are not coniferous, e.g. holly."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.679978Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-plastic-eventually-biodegrade-even-takes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Plastic will eventually biodegrade, even if it takes hundreds of years."@en ;
  curric:correction """Plastic is not biodegradable, it just breaks down into smaller and smaller pieces and eventually turns into microplastics (tiny plastic pieces, smaller than 5 mm)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680013Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-incinerarting-waste-good-environment
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Incinerarting waste is good for the environment."@en ;
  curric:correction "Incinerating waste releases toxic gases and carbon emissions."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680049Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-country-called-global-superpower-lot
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A country is called a global superpower if it has a lot of money."@en ;
  curric:correction """A global superpower is used to describe a country that has a lot of power or influence over other countries and places in the world. Different factors make a global superpower powerful such as economic, cultural, population and resources."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680218Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-one-ice-age
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "There has only been one ice age."@en ;
  curric:correction """There have been numerous periods of warming and cooling throughout Earth's history. This has meant there have been a number of ice ages throughout history."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680385Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-our-imports-uk-come-china
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Most of our imports in the UK come from China."@en ;
  curric:correction "Most of our imports in the UK come from the US and EU countries."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680434Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-supply-chains-start-manufacturing-stage
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Supply chains start at the manufacturing stage."@en ;
  curric:correction "Supply chains start when raw materials have been taken from the earth."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680497Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-hard-engineering-effective-protecting-flooding
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Hard engineering is always very effective at protecting from flooding."@en ;
  curric:correction """Channel straightening, dredging and embankments can all make flooding worse downstream, as the channel can hold more water and speed up the flow."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680644Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-flooding-happens-close-rivers
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Flooding only happens close to rivers."@en ;
  curric:correction """Flooding can also happen away from rivers, especially after heavy rainfall. When the ground can't absorb the water fast enough, surface water builds up and causes floods — even in places far from rivers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680651Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-sourcing-energy-renewables-fossil-fuels
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "We are sourcing more energy from renewables than fossil fuels."@en ;
  curric:correction "Over 80% of global energy still comes from coal, oil, and gas."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680670Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-possible-overweight-undernourished-same-time
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "It is not possible to be overweight and undernourished at the same time."@en ;
  curric:correction """Undernourishment occurs when someone isn’t receiving enough calories or essential nutrients to grow and function well. So it is possible to over eat but not eat enough of the right foods to acquire sufficient nutrients."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680728Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-maps-same
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All maps are the same."@en ;
  curric:correction """Different maps aim to show different things such as country borders, the location of physical features and the height of the land."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680802Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-governments-help-make-decisions-flood
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Only governments help make decisions on where flood protection is used."@en ;
  curric:correction "Many stakeholders are invloved in making decisions on flood defences."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680860Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-one-type-rock-rocks-cant
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "There is only one type of rock, and rocks can't change."@en ;
  curric:correction """Students will explore the three main types of rock found on Earth, and understand how rocks are recycled through the rock cycle."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680890Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-globalisation-world-becoming-developed
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Globalisation is the world becoming more developed."@en ;
  curric:correction "Globalisation is the world becoming more interconnected."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680897Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-attrition-rocks-sediment-carried-river
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Attrition is where rocks and sediment carried by the river collide with the bed and the banks causing pieces to break off."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Abrasion is where rocks and sediment carried by the river collide with the bed and the banks causing pieces to break off."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680924Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-uk-doesnt-experience-volcanic-activity
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The UK doesn't experience volcanic activity today, so volcanoes are not important to the UK's geological history."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The UK was once a volcanically active region due to its position near tectonic plate boundaries millions of years ago. Evidence of past volcanic activity includes: the Giant’s Causeway in Northern Ireland and the volcanic rocks in Snowdonia."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680929Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-water-same-mix
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students can think that all water is the same, or can mix up saltwater (seawater) and freshwater and where these are found."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Water on Earth is either saltwater or freshwater. Saltwater is found in seas and oceans, freshwater is found in rivers and streams. Only salt tolerant plants and animal species can survive in saltwater."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680960Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-soil-dirt
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Soil is just dirt."@en ;
  curric:correction """Soil is a complex and vital resource made of minerals, organic matter, water, and living organisms. It is important for growing food, storing carbon, and maintaining ecosystems. Without healthy soil, agriculture and natural habitats wouldn't survive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680976Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-globalisation-world-developing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Globalisation is about the world developing."@en ;
  curric:correction "Globalisation is about the world becoming more connected."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.680990Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-methane-cow-flatulence-causes-global
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Methane from cow flatulence causes global warming."@en ;
  curric:correction """Ruminant animals (like cows and sheep) produce methane during digestion, 90–95% of this is released through eructation (burping). Methane is a greenhouse gas, which insulates our planet."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.681390Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-middle-eastern-countries-rich-because
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All Middle Eastern countries are rich because they have oil."@en ;
  curric:correction """While oil is a major resource, not every country has it. Countries like Yemen and Jordan have little or no oil, which affects their economies differently."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.681436Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-get-command-language-describe
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils often get the command language of describe and explain mixed up, most often causing them to explain something when just a description has been asked for."""@en ;
  curric:correction """A description gives details of what something is like. It should contain as much detail as possible. An explanation gives reasons for the features and should use langauge such as 'because', 'as a result of', 'due to'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.681482Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-factor-viewed-independently
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Each factor can be viewed independently."@en ;
  curric:correction """To understand the climate of a place or when comparing the climates of places, the factors need to be considered collectively and each factor may have a different level of relevance."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.681700Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-antarctica-owned-group-countries
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Antarctica is owned by a group of countries."@en ;
  curric:correction """Antarctica is one of the global commons, meaning it belongs to all of humanity, not individual nations."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.681796Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-maps-accurate
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Maps are always accurate."@en ;
  curric:correction "Maps are never completely accurate."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.681889Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-customer-decisions-dont-make-difference
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Customer decisions don’t make a difference to global fish populations."@en ;
  curric:correction """Eating fish from well-managed fisheries helps prevent overfishing, protects marine biodiversity, and ensures fish populations remain healthy for future generations."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.681894Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-food-web-linear
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A food web is linear."@en ;
  curric:correction "A food web is not linear, it is complex and interconnected."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.681898Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-antarctica-ocean-covered-ice
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Antarctica is an ocean covered in ice."@en ;
  curric:correction """Antarctica is a continent, not an ocean. It has a landmass beneath its thick ice sheets, unlike the Arctic, which is sea ice floating on the ocean."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.681903Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-tendency-think-immediate-impacts
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils can have a tendency to think about the immediate impacts and not consider those over longer stretches of time."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Geographers need to think about diffferent dimensions of time i.e. short term and long term and use this as a framework to support understanding and evaluation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.681910Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-china-contributed-co-emissions
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "China has contributed most to CO₂ emissions."@en ;
  curric:correction """North America and Europe have contributed the most to total CO₂ emissions, mainly because they industrialised first (in the 1800s)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.681966Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-building-sustainable-future-responsibility-governments
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Building a more sustainable future is just the responsibility of governments."@en ;
  curric:correction """Building a more sustainable future takes action from all levels of society, inidviudals, community and government."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682018Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-everyone-nigeria-impacted-climate-change
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Everyone in Nigeria is impacted by climate change equally."@en ;
  curric:correction """Some people in Nigeria are impacted by climate change more than than others. Many different overlapping factors make some people more vulnerable to climate change impacts than others."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682037Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-forests-fenced-guarded-stop-illegal
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The forests should be fenced off and guarded to stop illegal logging."@en ;
  curric:correction """Forests span far too great an area for humans to guard or fence off. Therefore technology is used to help track forests and timber."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682132Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-india-much-smaller-greenland
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "India is much smaller than Greenland."@en ;
  curric:correction """India is similar in size to Greenland although looks much smaller on some projections of the world map."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682166Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-camels-store-water-their-humps
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Camels store water in their humps."@en ;
  curric:correction "Camels store fat in their humps for energy, not water."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682767Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-make-sweeping-statements-people
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils can make sweeping statements about people that live in places."@en ;
  curric:correction """It is important that data is used as an average and not the characteristics of every individual. The word stereotype is useful to use in this instance."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682777Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-housing-cities-better-bigger-cheaper
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That housing in cities is better / bigger / cheaper / more available than in rural areas."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Cities are often perceived to have better or more housing but this is not always the case. Inner city housing can be small and run down; people who move to cities may not find accomodation at all and may have to live in informal settlements."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682803Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-people-flee-their-home-due
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Most people who have to flee their home due to war will travel a long distance away from their country."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Although some refugees will travel a long distance, most people who have to leave quickly for their own safety will travel to a neighbouring country."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682819Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-cannot-grow-new-plants-desert
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "We cannot grow new plants in the desert, it is too dry."@en ;
  curric:correction """Plants can have special features, or adaptations, to help them survive in the desert. This, alongside new technology, means that plants can sustain life in the desert and overcome the issue of desertification."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682870Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-democratic-republic-congo-neighbouring-country
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That the Democratic Republic of the Congo and neighbouring country, the Republic of Congo, are the same country. Students can inadvertently shorten DRC to 'Congo' in verbal or written work."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The DRC and the Republic of Congo are two separate countries in central Africa. The Congo River forms part of the border between the countries; their capital cities Kinshasa and Brazzaville are located on oppposite banks of the river from each other."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682921Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-china-same-size-greenland
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "China is about the same size as Greenland."@en ;
  curric:correction """China is around four times the size of Greenland although it looks about the same size on some projections of the world map."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682968Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-run-oil-make
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "If we run out of oil, we can just make more."@en ;
  curric:correction """Fossil fuels take millions of years to form – much longer than a human lifetime. We can’t just “make” more. Once we use them up, they’re gone. That’s why we need to balance using them with finding cleaner, renewable alternatives."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.682996Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-development-driven-governments-big-international
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Development is always driven by governments and big international organisations."@en ;
  curric:correction """While governments and organisations play a big role, development often happens through smaller, community-led projects where local people take charge."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683007Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-countries-highest-gdp-per-capita
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Countries with the highest GDP per capita always have the highest healthy life expectancy."""@en ;
  curric:correction """This isn't always the case as other factors also play a big role, like access to healthcare, lifestyle, diet, pollution levels, and inequality."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.683064Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-economic-development-fully-explained-physical
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Economic development can be fully explained by physical geography."@en ;
  curric:correction """Physical geography is one factor in influencing a country’s development. Other factors such as history and politics often have a greater influence."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684148Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-gdp-per-capita-effective-way
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "GDP per capita is the most effective way to measure development."@en ;
  curric:correction """Although useful, GDP per capita is not as effective as composite indicators such as HDI, which include a measure of health and education"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.684377Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-migration-brings-people
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Migration just brings people."@en ;
  curric:correction "Migration brings other cultures, foods and fashion to the UK."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686082Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-inequality-refers-uneven-distribution-wealth
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Inequality just refers to the uneven distribution of wealth."@en ;
  curric:correction """Inequality is about more than wealth. It is the uneven distribution of resources, opportunities, and living conditions. It includes different categories such as economic, political, social, environmental and digital."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686416Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-quality-life-people-around-world
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The quality of life of people around the world is getting worse."@en ;
  curric:correction """In most places around the world, social indicators such as life expectancy and the average expected years of schooling, have increased."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686544Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-suez-canal-important-middle-east
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The Suez Canal is only important for the Middle East."@en ;
  curric:correction """The Suez Canal is important globally as 30% of all global container traffic and 12% of all global trade passes through the canal."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686625Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-natural-resources-natural-untouched-humans
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All natural resources are natural and untouched by humans."@en ;
  curric:correction """Many natural resources have been heavily managed, modified, or even created by humans, such as: managed forests, fish farms, or reservoirs."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686706Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-rocks-formed-same-geological-period
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All rocks formed during the same geological period will be similar."@en ;
  curric:correction """Although many rocks formed during the same geological period will be similar, volcanic processes may be creating rocks at the same time as sedimentary rocks are being created. These rocks will be very different and create contrasting landscapes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686725Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-historical-factors-longer-impact-global
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Historical factors no longer impact on global inequality around the world."@en ;
  curric:correction """There is an enduring impact of history on global inequality. Historical factors have shaped wealth, opportunities, and power today."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686753Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-its-fine-adapt-mitigate-dont
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "It's fine to adapt or mitigate, we don't need to do both."@en ;
  curric:correction """Adaptation helps us cope with climate change, but it doesn’t stop the problem from getting worse. Mitigation helps slow down climate change. The best approach is to use both mitigation and adaptation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686838Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-everyone-middle-east-lives-desert
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Everyone in the Middle East lives in the desert."@en ;
  curric:correction """Although deserts cover a vast amount of land, people tend to cluster around water sources like rivers and coasts. That’s why cities like Cairo (near the Nile) are densely populated."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686879Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-beijing-inhabited-people-recently
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Beijing was only inhabited by people recently."@en ;
  curric:correction """People are thought to have inhabited the area around Beijing since the Stone Age, hundreds of thousands of years ago."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686888Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-climate-change-simply-means-hotter
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Climate change simply means hotter, drier summers in the UK."@en ;
  curric:correction """Warmer temperatures in summer and fewer cold spells in winter are due to climate change. There is also some evidence that the UK is also experiencing more heavy rain events."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686900Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-confusion-difference-global-cities-megacities
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Confusion about the difference between global cities and megacities."@en ;
  curric:correction """Global cities are well-connected cities that are recognised as being of global importance. Megacities are cities with more than 10 million inhabitants. Not all global cities are megacities."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686915Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-deforestation-logging-same-thing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That deforestation and logging are the same thing."@en ;
  curric:correction """Logging is the use of trees as a natural resource for their wood and can happen legally or illegaly. Deforestation is the cutting down of trees for many reasons, often to make space for other activities such as mining, road building or farming."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686921Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-countries-same-shape-size-same
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That countries are always the same shape and size, with the same borders and the same name throughout their history and that these aspects will never change."""@en ;
  curric:correction """History has shown that in many countries borders move, countries expand or shrink and the name of any given country is not fixed and permanent. These things are often the result of conflict or warfare which causes significant political change."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686956Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-middle-east-desert-rivers
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The Middle East is all desert and has no rivers."@en ;
  curric:correction """Students will explore the Tigris and Euphrates and understand how they created ancient civilisations and continue to support farming today."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686962Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-natural-resources-found-deep-underground
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That all natural resources are found deep underground and so need to be mined to extract them."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Some natural resources are found deep underground, like ores of some metals and fossil fuels. Others are not found underground, for example the rainforest trees that are used for timber or as a source of rubber, or water sources like lakes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686971Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-people-live-volcanoes-because-dangerous
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "People do not live on volcanoes because it is too dangerous."@en ;
  curric:correction """One in twenty people live close to an active volcano, as there are many attractive qualities to living there, e.g. fertile soils, tourist income and geothermal energy."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.686980Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-inequality-difference-much-money-people
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Inequality is just about the difference in how much money people have."@en ;
  curric:correction """There are many different inequalities between people’s lives such as access to education and health care, quality of housing, job opportunities and how people are treated."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687038Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-population-density-same-everywhere-china
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Population density is the same everywhere in China."@en ;
  curric:correction """Population density varies across China; urban areas such as Shanghai are densely populated, but rural areas, such as the mountainous regions covering much of western China, are sparsely populated."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687063Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-greenhouse-effect-negative-impact
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The greenhouse effect has a negative impact."@en ;
  curric:correction """The greenhouse effect is a natural process that is essential for life on Earth. Without it, our planet would be too cold to sustain most life forms."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687068Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-everyone-china-around-world-equally
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Everyone in China and around the world is equally responsible for climate change."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Although everyone has a carbon footprint, some people and places contribute more to climate change than others."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687072Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-everyone-impacted-climate-change-equally
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Everyone is impacted by climate change equally."@en ;
  curric:correction """Although everyone is affected by climate change, some people and places are impacted more than others."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687106Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-deserts-found-hot-climates
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Deserts are only found in very hot climates."@en ;
  curric:correction """Deserts are areas with extremely low rainfall and can be hot or cold depending on where they are located. The Gobi Desert is a cold desert."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687155Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-migration-middle-east-forced-due
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All migration in the Middle East is forced due to conflict."@en ;
  curric:correction """While war and displacement are significant in parts of the Middle East, the region is also a major destination for voluntary economic migration, especially to the Gulf States like the UAE, Qatar, and Saudi Arabia."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687286Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-dangerous-earthquake-event-ground-shakes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """A dangerous earthquake event is when the ground shakes, once. Then the danger is over."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Further sizeable earthquakes may occur in the days, weeks and months after a big earthquake, known as aftershocks, and these can be as dangerous for people and property, especially given the damage already done."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.687354Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-lagos-capital-nigeria
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Lagos is the capital of Nigeria."@en ;
  curric:correction """Lagos became the capital of an independent Nigeria in 1960 but was replaced by Abuja in 1991."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.688329Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-weather-associated-anticyclone-stays-same
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The weather associated with an anticyclone stays the same all year around."@en ;
  curric:correction """Students will analyse images to identify how anticyclones may bring different weather in the summer and winter."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.690377Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-one-type-rain-same
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "There is only one type of rain; it is all the same."@en ;
  curric:correction """Students will be exposed to the three different types of rainfall: relief, convectional, frontal."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.690854Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-coastlines-sandy-beaches
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That all coastlines are sandy beaches."@en ;
  curric:correction """Not all coastlines are sandy beaches. Some coastlines have beaches of stones called shingle, and some coastlines only have cliffs without any beach."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.691108Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-wind-farms-best-located-remotely
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Wind farms are best located as remotely as possible."@en ;
  curric:correction """Wind farms should be located far from densely populated areas but close to the electricity grid. If they are too remote, the cost of connecting them to the grid will be high."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692270Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-contours-used-show-hills-mountains
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Contours are only used to show hills and mountains."@en ;
  curric:correction """Contours are used to show the height of the land at 10 metre intervals above sea level."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692928Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-river-energy-upper-course
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A river has the most energy in the upper course."@en ;
  curric:correction """The river does not have that much energy in the upper course as there is not a lot of water in the river."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.692932Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-poaching-involves-trophy-animals-like
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That poaching only involves 'trophy' animals like elephants and wild cats."@en ;
  curric:correction """Poaching happens on a daily basis all around the world as a means of organised illegal activity (but in some cases for survival). It can include any animal species, large or small, that has a perceived value in its meat, skin, or another biproduct."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.693409Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-maps-same-symbols
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Maps always have the same symbols."@en ;
  curric:correction "You find different symbols depending on the scale of your map."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.693903Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-colder-coast-because-near-water
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "It is always colder at the coast because it is near water."@en ;
  curric:correction """Students will understand that, in winter, coastal areas tend to be warmer because water takes longer to heat up."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.694412Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-weathering-erosion-same-process
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Weathering and erosion are the same process."@en ;
  curric:correction """Weathering breaks down rocks in place without movement, while erosion involves the removal and transport of that material by wind, water, ice, or gravity."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.695765Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-one-source-river
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "There is one source to a river."@en ;
  curric:correction "There can be many different sources within a drainage basin system."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.695904Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-population-density-same-everywhere-india
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Population density is the same everywhere in India."@en ;
  curric:correction """Population density varies across India; urban areas are densely populated, but rural areas, such as much of the Himalayas, are sparsely populated."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.697386Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-rains-monsoon-season
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "It always rains during the monsoon season."@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain that the rainfall intensity and frequency during the monsoon season can vary from year to year. Although it can rain every or most days, this is often a short period of intense rainfall followed by a period of dry conditions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.697696Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-industrial-cities-decline-once-their
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All industrial cities decline once their factories close."@en ;
  curric:correction """Some cities, like Sheffield, adapt by developing new industries, services, and cultural attractions after industrial decline."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.697894Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-geography-learning-natural-world
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Geography is learning about the natural world."@en ;
  curric:correction """Geography has many different aspects and includes learning about the natural world and learning about society."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698062Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-living-cities-means-dealing-problems
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Living in cities only means dealing with problems like noise and crowds."@en ;
  curric:correction """While cities can have challenges like noise and crowds, they also offer many benefits such as better jobs, healthcare, education, cultural events, and opportunities to meet people from different backgrounds."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.698465Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-everyone-high-income-countries-uk
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Everyone in high-income countries in the UK is wealthier than people in low-income countries like Kenya."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The average income in the UK is higher than in Kenya, but there is a big variation in both countries. There are very wealthy people in Kenya and people on very low incomes in the UK."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699143Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-wildfires-ignited-naturally
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Wildfires are all ignited naturally."@en ;
  curric:correction """Wildfires can be ignited by natural (e.g. lightning) or human causes (e.g. campfires)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699211Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-migrants-forced-move
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All migrants are forced to move."@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain that there are different reasons which can lead to someone migrating. These might be related to work, education, family, better services, living environment or safety. Spend time discussing these in more detail."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699215Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-trade-goods
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "You can only trade goods."@en ;
  curric:correction "You can trade goods and services such as education and finance services."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699222Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-geological-timescales-go-back-far
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Geological timescales go back as far as human history."@en ;
  curric:correction "Geological timescales are much greater than human history."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699227Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-tncs-sell-same-products-different
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "TNCs sell the same products in different countries."@en ;
  curric:correction "TNCs can sell different products in different countries."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699337Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-living-standards-quality-life-same
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Living standards and quality of life are the same."@en ;
  curric:correction """Living standards are about the the level of necessities and comforts of daily life that is available to and affordable by a person."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699358Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-birth-rates-death-rates-total
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That birth rates and death rates are the total number of people who have been born or died."""@en ;
  curric:correction "Birth and death rates are per 1 000 people per year."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699400Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-mumbai-inhabited-people-recently
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Mumbai was only inhabited by people recently."@en ;
  curric:correction """People are thought to have first inhabited Mumbai in the Stone Age, hundreds of thousands of years ago."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699424Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-frequently-mix-different-types
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students frequently mix up the different types of processes, their names and definitions."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Flag up words for processes that sound similar or have similar spellings as you encounter them. Signpost the differences in their meanings, and encourage students to highlight them in a way that is most useful for them, for example by colour coding."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699434Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-rising-sea-levels-affect-places
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That rising sea levels only affect a few places like tropical islands, and that cities are not at risk of rising sea levels."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Rising sea levels is a concern for all global coastal communities. There is nowhere with a coast that will not be affected by rising sea levels, including major global cities, although some communities are affected more than others."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699439Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-rare-earth-materials-rare
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Rare earth materials are rare."@en ;
  curric:correction """Despite their name, they’re not actually rare in quantity, they’re just rarely found in concentrated, economically viable deposits."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699554Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-geological-resources-bad-because-damage
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Geological resources are all bad because they damage the environment."@en ;
  curric:correction """While they can cause environmental harm, they also provide essential materials and economic benefits. The key is understanding both advantages and disadvantages—which is what geographers evaluate."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699559Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-ocean-acidification-water-polluted-human
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Ocean acidification is when water is polluted from human activities on land."@en ;
  curric:correction """Ocean acidification is when the ocean absorbs extra carbon dioxide (CO₂) from the air, which makes the water more acidic."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699581Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-moscow-represents-life-russia
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Moscow represents life in Russia."@en ;
  curric:correction """Moscow is not representative of all of Russia; life in other regions can be very different. Moscow is the richest and most developed part of the country and other regions vary in terms of culture, economy, and infrastructure."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699586Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-migration-negative-impacts
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Migration only has negative impacts."@en ;
  curric:correction """Migration also brings benefits such as skills and expertise for the jobs market, economic benefits and a more diverse society."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699591Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-climate-change-going-cause-planet
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Climate change is going to cause the planet to get hotter and drier."@en ;
  curric:correction """The planet is getting hotter. Some places are going to get hotter whereas some places are going to get wetter."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699595Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-temperate-grasslands-places-world-cereal
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Temperate grasslands are the only places in the world where cereal crops are grown."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Whilst temperate grasslands are significant providers of much of the world’s wheat and other cereal crops and referred to as 'breadbaskets', they are not the only places in the world where these crops are grown."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699623Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-russia-benefit-climate-change-because
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Russia will benefit from climate change because it will make the country warmer, allowing for more agriculture and economic opportunities."""@en ;
  curric:correction """While warming may open up some land for agriculture, the negative impacts will outweigh potential benefits. For example, flooding and unpredictable weather patterns will harm crops and water supplies."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699674Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-south-america-south-american-plate
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "South America and the South American plate are the same thing."@en ;
  curric:correction """South America is a continent (land), whereas the South American plate also includes part of the Atlantic ocean."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699679Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-urban-regeneration-means-building-new
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Urban regeneration only means building new houses."@en ;
  curric:correction """Regeneration is not just about new housing—it also improves transport, creates jobs, and provides community services."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699760Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-lava-magma-used-interchangeably
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Lava and magma can be used interchangeably."@en ;
  curric:correction """Magma is molten rock underground, whereas lava is molten rock above Earth's surface."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699764Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-megacities-global-cities-because-big
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All megacities are global cities because they are so big."@en ;
  curric:correction """Not all megacities are global cities. While megacities have populations of over 10 million, global cities are defined by their international influence in areas such as finance, culture, politics, and transport."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699769Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-hydroponic-aquaponic-systems-completely-self
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Hydroponic and aquaponic systems are completely self-sustaining or maintenance-free."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Require regular monitoring, energy inputs and human intervention to stay productive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699795Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-big-cities-rich-countries-cause
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Only big cities in rich countries cause climate change."@en ;
  curric:correction """Cities of all sizes, in both rich and poorer countries, contribute to climate change through emissions, especially from transport, energy use, and waste."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699822Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-living-conditions-better-urban-areas
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Living conditions are always better in urban areas than rural areas."@en ;
  curric:correction """There is a wide variety of living conditions within, as well as between, rural and urban communities."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699827Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-cities-cant-much-stop-climate
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Cities can’t do much to stop climate change because it’s a global problem."@en ;
  curric:correction """While climate change is a global issue, cities can make a big difference by reducing emissions and adapting their infrastructure to protect people and the environment."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699834Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-places-experience-rain-particularly-heavy
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That places which experience rain, particularly heavy rain as in the DRC, musn't experience water scarcity or drought."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Heavy rainfall is experienced in some parts of the DRC such as rainforests whilst other parts such as savanna are very dry. Furthermore rainforests are depleting and savanna is expanding as global temperatures are rising, increasing risks of drought."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699838Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-sustainability-protecting-environment
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Sustainability is only about protecting the environment."@en ;
  curric:correction """Sustainability also includes improving people’s lives and meeting their needs fairly."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699854Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-population-pyramids-pyramid-shaped
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All population pyramids are pyramid-shaped."@en ;
  curric:correction """Population pyramids can have different shapes depending on demographic factors. Some may be more rectangular or even inverted, reflecting various population structures."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699859Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-important-rainforest-protect-amazon-other
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That the most important rainforest to protect is the Amazon and that other rainforests are smaller so they don't matter as much."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Tropical rainforests are rich in biodiversity and play a crucial role in regulating Earth's climate as carbon sinks. Rainforests in Africa or Asia are as important as the Amazon in South America, so global climate action is needed to protect them."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.699871Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-congo-rainforest-found-drc
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That the Congo rainforest is only found in the DRC."@en ;
  curric:correction """The Congo rainforest is found in the Congo Basin, which spans six countries in Africa: Cameroon, Central African Republic, Democratic Republic of the Congo, Republic of the Congo, Equatorial Guinea and Gabon."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700223Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-weather-climate-same
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that weather and climate are the same."@en ;
  curric:correction """Pupils will explore that weather is the short term changes in the atmosphere whereas climate is long term changes in the atmospheric patterns of a place."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700300Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-northings-come-eastings
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Northings come before eastings."@en ;
  curric:correction "Eastings come first, then northings."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700726Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-proportional-data-presented-using-pie
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Proportional data can only be presented using a pie chart."@en ;
  curric:correction """A pie chart is by far the most common method that geographers use, but any shape can be split into proportional sections."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700731Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-population-pyramids-show-us-total
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Population pyramids only show us the total population size."@en ;
  curric:correction """A population pyramid provides information about the structure of the population; the age and gender profile of the location represented. This can help governments with future planning."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.700736Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-climate-change-causes-global-warming
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That climate change causes global warming, or that climate change and global warming are the same thing."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Global warming is the rise in average temperatures as a result of the greenhouse effect. Climate change is changes to weather patterns (including temperatures and rainfall patterns) as a result of global warming."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.701121Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-tsunamis-big-waves
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Tsunamis are just big waves."@en ;
  curric:correction """Tsunamis are caused by displacement of the ocean, not wind blowing over the surface. Tsunami waves don’t break, they come as a fast-moving wall of water, which can be far bigger and faster than a normal wave. They can also flood kilometres inland."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.701126Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-middle-east-desert
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The Middle East is all desert."@en ;
  curric:correction "The Middle East is so vast that it contains a number of different biomes."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.701647Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-boycotting-palm-oil-helps-stop
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Boycotting palm oil helps stop deforestation."@en ;
  curric:correction """Experts recommend supporting certified sustainable palm oil, as palm oil is the most land-efficient oil crop. Replacing it with less efficient crops like sunflowers could cause more deforestation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.701766Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-around-one-quarter-water-found
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Around one quarter of water is found on land."@en ;
  curric:correction "Only 0.9% of water is stored on land."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.701772Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-os-maps-use-same-scale
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "OS maps all use the same scale."@en ;
  curric:correction "OS maps have different scales."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.702418Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-glaciers-made-salt-water
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Glaciers are made of salt water"@en ;
  curric:correction "Glaciers are made of fresh water from snow and rain"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.702653Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-coastal-defences-stop
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students may think that coastal defences stop erosion entirely."@en ;
  curric:correction """Coastal defences aim to protect the coastline from erosion, and can greatly reduce erosion but they can't stop it completely. Defences don't last forever, so eventually the power of the sea will regain strength in areas previously protected."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.703167Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-gender-inequality-same-around-world
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Gender inequality is the same around the world."@en ;
  curric:correction "Gender inequality varies around the world."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.703244Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-plate-boundaries-clean-cuts-ground
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Plate boundaries are clean cuts through the ground which separate two plates."@en ;
  curric:correction """There is not one fault but many, which make up a plate boundary and the rock is locked together across the two plates."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.703248Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-physical-geography-nigeria-similar-everywhere
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The physical geography of Nigeria is very similar everywhere in the country."@en ;
  curric:correction """Nigeria has a range of physical features. These include rivers, plateaux, mountains, savannas, deserts and coastlines."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.703376Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-gis-show-one-set-data
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "GIS can only show one set of data."@en ;
  curric:correction "GIS can show multiple layers of data as well as change over time."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.703381Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-rivers-cant-flow-areas-low
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Rivers can't flow through areas with very low rainfall totals."@en ;
  curric:correction """Rivers often flow through different climate zones, therefore their source may be in a mountainous area with high rainfall totals, but they may then flow through arid areas to the sea."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.703387Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-stopping-deforestation-means-preventing-felling
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Stopping deforestation just means preventing the felling of trees."@en ;
  curric:correction """There are many approaches to preventing and even reversing deforestation not just one, for example national parks, selective logging, small-scale agroforestry and ecotourism."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.703553Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-melting-sea-ice-impact-ocean
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Melting sea ice does not impact ocean currents."@en ;
  curric:correction """Melting ice alters the balance of freshwater and saltwater in the ocean, which can disrupt major ocean currents like the Gulf Stream."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.703612Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-coastal-erosion-likely-same-different
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Coastal erosion is likely to be the same in different places along a stretch of coastline."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Coastal erosion varies between different places. It is influenced by human factors, such as whether coastal defences have been installed, and physical factors, such as the rock type."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.703906Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-physical-geography-india-doesnt-vary
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The physical geography of India doesn't vary across the country."@en ;
  curric:correction """Use GIS or atlases to investigate how India's phyiscal geography varies across the country."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.704168Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-energy-source-produced-anywhere
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Any energy source can be produced anywhere."@en ;
  curric:correction "Human and physical geography must be considered when locating energy sources."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.704172Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-cities-growing-same-rate-everywhere
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Cities are growing at the same rate everywhere around the world."@en ;
  curric:correction """Cities are growing at different rates around the world. Often, cities in countries with a lower HDI are growing more rapidly than cities in countries with a higher HDI."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.704255Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-points-channel-profile-joined-using
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Points in a channel profile should be joined using a ruler."@en ;
  curric:correction """Points in a channel profile should be drawn with a slight curve to more accurately represent the shape of the river channel."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.704320Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-good-maths-able-use-statistical
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """You have to be good at maths to be able to use statistical tests in geographical enquiries."""@en ;
  curric:correction """You have to know how to interpret the results of statistical tests to use them in geographical enquiries."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.704665Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-tests-run-gm-crops-found
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All the tests run on GM crops have found that they create no health issues."@en ;
  curric:correction """Most major scientific bodies find no conclusive evidence of harm from approved GM foods, which have all been tested. However, some animal studies raise questions, and critics argue that long-term human studies are limited."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.704672Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-anomalous-data-ignored-data-analysis
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Anomalous data can be ignored in the data analysis stage as it is due to human error in the data collection stage."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Geographers will always try to find explanations for data that does not fit the general trend before they dismiss it as being caused by human error during the data collection stage."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.704677Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-someone-survives-injured-earthquake-safe
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """If someone survives and is not injured during the earthquake, they are then safe."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Since many survivors had to stay in crowded shelters or sleep outside, the risk of diseases increased. In addition, strong aftershocks hit the area, damaging buildings that were already unstable."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.704682Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-uks-climate-same-across-country
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The UK’s climate is the same across the country."@en ;
  curric:correction """Students will understand that the UK’s climate varies between different regions due to latitude, altitude and air masses."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.704688Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-climate-russia-cold
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The climate of Russia is always cold."@en ;
  curric:correction "The climate of Russia varies across its territory and across the year."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.705347Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-cities-grow-because-migration
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Cities only grow because of migration."@en ;
  curric:correction """While migration is a key factor, natural increase (more births than deaths) is often just as important - especially in cities with young populations."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.705406Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-nuclear-energy-either-renewable-source
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Nuclear energy is either a renewable source of energy or a fossil fuel."@en ;
  curric:correction "Nuclear energy is a non-renewable energy source but is not a fossil fuel."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.705644Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-microplastics-found-ocean
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Microplastics are only found in the ocean."@en ;
  curric:correction "Microplastics are found in the ocean, soil, rock and animals."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.705908Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-direction-prevailing-wind-direction-wind
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That the direction of the prevailing wind is the direction that the wind is blowing in at any particular time."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The prevailing wind is wind from a particular direction that is most frequently experienced in a location. Winds can come from other directions, especially in stormy conditions, but they are not the same as the prevailing wind."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.705914Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-oceanic-plate-subducts-destructive-plate
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The oceanic plate subducts at a destructive plate margin and melts to form magma."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The water in the oceanic plate lowers the melting point, helping mantle rocks above to melt and form magma, not the subducting plate itself."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.705919Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-christianity-oldest-religion-originated-middle
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Christianity is the oldest religion that originated in the Middle East."@en ;
  curric:correction "Judaism is almost 2000 years older than Christianity."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.705925Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-challenges-facing-lagos-arent-problems
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The challenges facing Lagos aren’t problems in other cities."@en ;
  curric:correction "Many of the challenges facing Lagos are issues in most of the world’s cities."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.706095Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-fieldwork-take-place-unfamiliar-location
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Fieldwork must take place in an unfamiliar location."@en ;
  curric:correction """While it can be exciting to do fieldwork in a new place, fieldwork actually can take place anywhere."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.706100Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-areas-high-wind-speeds-colder
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Areas of high wind speeds are colder."@en ;
  curric:correction """While windy areas may feel colder on our bodies, geographers measure air temperature which is unlikely to be affected by the strength of the wind speed."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.706130Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-western-culture-refers-north-america
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Western culture refers to only North America."@en ;
  curric:correction "Western culture refers to North America, Europe and Australia."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.706247Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-nigeria-relatively-small-country
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Nigeria is a relatively small country."@en ;
  curric:correction """Nigeria is a relatively large country. It is much bigger than France despite it looking a similar size on some map projections."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.706251Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-topical-rainforests-cold-wet
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Topical rainforests are cold and wet."@en ;
  curric:correction """In tropical rainforests it is hot, this heat actually causes the rain by creating a lot of evaporation and rising air, which then cools and condenses to form clouds which rain."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.706471Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-subjective-data-automatically-invalid-ignored
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Subjective data is automatically invalid and should be ignored."@en ;
  curric:correction """Geographers use subjective data a lot as they value people's, and their own, opinion about something."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.706476Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-population-density-same-across-uk
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Population density is the same across the UK."@en ;
  curric:correction """Population density varies widely due to factors like topography and urbanisation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.706783Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-assumptions-interpretations-geographical-analysis-equally
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Assumptions and interpretations in geographical analysis are equally valid."@en ;
  curric:correction """Geographers should always aim to interpret their data accurately rather than make assumptions about it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.706787Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-field-sketches-artistic-impressions-geographical
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Field sketches are artistic impressions of a geographical scene."@en ;
  curric:correction """Field sketches are about clearly representing the geographical features of a place, not about the artistic skills of the geographer."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.706854Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-services-grow-same-pace-population
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Services grow at the same pace as population in cities."@en ;
  curric:correction """When the population of a city grows rapidly, often the growth of services is slower. In the twenty-first century this is particularly the case in rapidly developing countries, where lots of people arrive into cities each year."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.707031Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-purpose-data-presentation-make-data
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The purpose of data presentation is to make the data more attractive."@en ;
  curric:correction """The purpose of data presentation is to allow geographers to identify patterns and relationships in the data."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.707036Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-secondary-data-collected-expert-data
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Secondary data has to have been collected by an expert in the data and the topic area."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Though geographers often use secondary data that has been researched and produced by experts, it does not have to be: it can come from other students."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.707242Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-forests-same
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All forests are the same."@en ;
  curric:correction """Different forests have unique characteristics and ecosystems. The boreal forest, for example, is characterised by its cold climate and coniferous trees."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.707246Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-latitude-lines-run-vertically-earth
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Latitude lines run vertically down the Earth."@en ;
  curric:correction "Latitude lines run horizontally while longitude lines run vertically."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.707253Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-population-density-same-everywhere
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Population density is the same everywhere."@en ;
  curric:correction """This misconception arises because students may not realise that geographical factors vary widely. Address this by comparing different regions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.707257Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-drc-relatively-small-country
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The DRC is a relatively small country."@en ;
  curric:correction """The DRC is a very large country. It's position on the equator means that it often appears smaller than it really is on some world maps."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.707265Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-truncated-spurs-created-soley-glaciers
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Truncated spurs are created soley by glaciers."@en ;
  curric:correction """Truncated spurs started as interlocking spurs which are a fluvial feature formed by rivers. Glaciers then modify this landform through erosion."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.707318Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-gis-web-maps-tool-visualising
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """GIS web maps are only a tool for visualising geographical patterns in data; they can't help us explain geographical patterns."""@en ;
  curric:correction """GIS are a useful tool to visualise, interpret and analyse geographical data. This means they can be used to explain geographical patterns by comparing different layers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.707478Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-migrants-refugees
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All migrants are refugees"@en ;
  curric:correction """Not all migrants are refugees; some move for economic or educational reasons. Explain the differences between refugees and other migrants."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.707482Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-globalisation-beneficial-large-companies
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Globalisation is only beneficial to large companies."@en ;
  curric:correction "Globalisation can improve the quality of life of people."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.707584Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-grykes-clints-type
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Some students may think that grykes and clints are type of rock, rather than being a feature of limestone landscapes."""@en ;
  curric:correction "Students will be taught what clints and grykes are in relation to limestone."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.707589Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-large-soil-particles-means-smaller
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Large soil particles means there are smaller pores between them."@en ;
  curric:correction """Soil that is made-up of small particles has a structure where the particles can fit together more easily reducing the pore size between them."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.707801Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-dubai-rich-because-oil
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Dubai is only rich because of oil."@en ;
  curric:correction """Whilst oil funded Dubai’s early growth, it now contributes only a small part of its GDP. Tourism, finance, and trade are the dominant economic drivers today."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.707807Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-physical-geography-china-doesnt-vary
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The physical geography of China doesn't vary across the country."@en ;
  curric:correction """China is a huge country with diverse landscapes and a range of biomes including desert, grassland, tropical forests and temperate forests."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.707919Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-cities-grow-randomly-without-structure
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Cities grow randomly without any structure or planning."@en ;
  curric:correction """In reality, urban land use is often influenced by models (like the Burgess or Hoyt models), and factors such as history, economics, transport links, and the environment shape how cities develop and function over time."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.707924Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-waves-tides-same-thing-tides
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That waves and tides are the same thing, or that tides are the cause of waves, or that wind causes both waves and tides."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Waves are caused by the wind blowing across the sea, not by the tide. The tide is the regular rise and fall of the sea level regardless of whether there are waves or if the sea is calm."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.707928Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-earthquakes-volcanoes-happen-tectonic-plates
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Earthquakes and volcanoes happen on tectonic plates."@en ;
  curric:correction """Tectonic plates cover the whole world, this would mean they happen everywhere. The majority of earthquakes and volcanoes occur at plate boundaries (where two plates meet), though there are some which happen away from boundaries."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.707935Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-countries-ageing-populations
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All countries have ageing populations."@en ;
  curric:correction """Not all countries have ageing populations. It is more common in higher income nations with longer life expectancies."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.708027Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-government-drc-concerned-military-defence
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That the government of the DRC is only concerned with the military and defence and not with other important matters that affect the people."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The government of the DRC has many departments focussed on a variety of areas from energy and industries to farming and conservation. The government makes policies and pledges in a number of contexts, not only in defence and military matters."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.708031Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-sea-level-constantly-same-elevation
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That sea level is constantly the same and that elevation is the same as height in general."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Sea level changes with the tides; the measure that we use as a baseline is the mean (average) sea level. This is used to calculate elevation of geographical features; sea level is taken as zero and every 1 metre in height is 1 metre above sea level."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.708082Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-lake-district-lakes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The Lake District only has lakes."@en ;
  curric:correction """While famous for its lakes, the region also features mountains, forests, and valleys, including England’s highest peak, Scafell Pike."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.708181Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-animals-arctic-camouflaged-white-fur
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Animals in the Arctic are camouflaged with white fur all year round."@en ;
  curric:correction "The Arctic fox is camouflaged with white fur in winter and brown fur in summer."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.708186Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-jeans-come-one-place
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Jeans come from one place."@en ;
  curric:correction "Jeans come from many different places."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.708275Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-middle-east-already-hot-dry
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The Middle East is already hot and dry, so climate change won’t really affect it."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Climate change will continue to make the region hotter and drier, which will have consequences such as desertification, water scarcity and food shortages."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.708390Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-china-produces-greenhouse-gases-per
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "China produces the most greenhouse gases per capita in the world."@en ;
  curric:correction """China produces the most greenhouse gases in the world, but with a population of over 1.4 billion people, their per capita emissions are significantly lower than many other countries."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.708584Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-overpopulation-underpopulation-number-people-country
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Overpopulation and underpopulation are only about the number of people in a country."""@en ;
  curric:correction """It’s not just about numbers—it’s about how well a country’s resources match the needs of its population."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.708588Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-renewable-energy-expensive-set
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Renewable energy is always expensive to set up."@en ;
  curric:correction """Small-scale renewable energy projects such as micro-hydro plants can be fairly cheap and help communities in lower income countries."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.708894Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-superpower-refers-countrys-military-power
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A superpower only refers to a country's military power and influence."@en ;
  curric:correction """Superpower status depends on a country's economy, population, military, energy reserves and cultural power."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.709019Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-glaciers-white
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Glaciers are white."@en ;
  curric:correction "Glaciers can appear dirty because they carry material."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.709115Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-digital-maps-used-locate-places
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Digital maps are only used to locate places."@en ;
  curric:correction "Digital maps are used in many different jobs and used to present data."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.709390Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-earthquakes-predicted-weeks-days-happen
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Earthquakes can be predicted a few weeks or days before they happen so that people can evacuate."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Humans can calculate the probability of an earthquake happening within a region, over a long period of time. It is not possible to predict exactly when or where earthquakes will occur, or of what size."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.709395Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-lava-dangerous-aspect-volcanic-eruption
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Lava is the only dangerous aspect to a volcanic eruption and you can just run out of the way."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Ash, lahars and pyroclastic flows are all extremely dangerous volcanic hazards. Pyroclastic flows can reach speeds of 435 mph, which is faster than a car."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.709399Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-matter-aspects-data-presented-axis
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """It does not matter which aspects of the data are presented on which axis of a graph."""@en ;
  curric:correction """It is a common convention for the independent variable to be read from the x-axis and the dependent variable to be read from the y-axis."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.709445Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-believe-mass-movement-occurs
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may believe that mass movement only occurs in mountainous areas or during extreme weather events."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Mass movement can happen anywhere there are slopes, even in places with mild weather conditions. While extreme weather can trigger events, even light rainfall can cause mass movement if the slope is steep or the material is already weathered."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.709520Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-levees-man-made
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Levees are man made."@en ;
  curric:correction "Levees can be built as a flood defence but they can also be created naturally."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.709747Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-colours-geographers-use-their-data
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The colours geographers use in their data presentation are always randomly chosen."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The colours geographers use are often associated with social conventions such as red being negative and green being positive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.709777Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-urbanisation-happens-rich-countries
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Urbanisation only happens in rich countries."@en ;
  curric:correction """Urbanisation is occurring fastest in low and middle income countries due to rapid population growth and rural to urban migration"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.709782Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-world-equally-interconnected
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All of the world is equally interconnected."@en ;
  curric:correction """Some parts of the world are more interconnected than others. It is influenced by many factors including wealth and size."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.709789Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-animals-adapt-different-conditions
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Only animals adapt to different conditions."@en ;
  curric:correction "Many plants and animals adapt in many different ways to their surroundings."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.710098Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-tourism-mer-de-glace-negative
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Tourism at the Mer de Glace only has negative impacts."@en ;
  curric:correction """Tourism at the Mer de Glace has both positive and negative impacts. Positive impacts include boosts to the local economy and an awareness of climate change."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.710102Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-everyone-involved-invested-plan-want
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That everyone involved or invested in a plan must want said coastal management project to happen to protect the coastline of an area."""@en ;
  curric:correction """In almost all cases, there are a wide range of opinions about coastal management projects, some in support of the plans and others not in favour for various reasons that they feel are important."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.710277Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-removing-mangroves-coast-affect-people
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Removing mangroves on the coast will not affect people inland or out at sea."@en ;
  curric:correction """Mangroves provide many services, including flood protection for settlements inland and nurseries for young fish (who may be caught for food when they have grown and left the protection of the mangroves)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.710281Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-grassroots-development-invented-western-thinkers
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Grassroots development was invented by western thinkers."@en ;
  curric:correction """In reality, many communities around the world have practiced grassroots development for centuries, using their own knowledge and solutions before Western ideas became popular."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.710286Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-angle-line-best-fit-tells
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The angle of the line of best fit tells geographers how strong the correlation is between two variables."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The strength of the correlation is decided by how close the plots are to the line of best fit."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.710291Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-describing-patterns-distribution-maps-pupils
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """When describing patterns of distribution from maps pupils can make the mistake of including information not available on the map itself and get tempted to explain patterns."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Use only the available information to write a description of what you see on the map including the general pattern and specific details provided by the legend, labels, compass rose and scale."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.710403Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-russia-ussr-same
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Russia and the USSR are the same."@en ;
  curric:correction """Russia was the largest part of the USSR, but they are not the same. The USSR was a union of 15 republics, including Russia. It dissolved in 1991, and each republic, like Ukraine and Georgia, became independent."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.710408Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-weather-forecasts-seen-apps-tv
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Weather forecasts are only seen on apps and on the TV. Weather forecasts just use symbols."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Students will explore synoptic charts, used by meteorologists, to interpret the weather."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.710413Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-climate-change-entirely-caused-humans
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Climate change is entirely caused by humans."@en ;
  curric:correction """Students will recognise that our climate changes naturally and there are physical causes of this. Humans have intensified the process in recent years."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:18.710580Z"^^xsd:dateTime .
